        <h2>About Us</h2>
          <p>
            The Loggerhead Shrike (Lanius ludovicianus) is one of two species of shrike that occur in North America and the only species of shrike world-wide that has an exclusively North American range.  The shrike is a robin-sized songbird with a raptor-like hooked bill, grey body with a black face-mask, and black wings with a prominent white wing patch.  Easily confused with the Northern Shrike (Lanius excubitor), the Loggerhead is smaller in size and its face mask extends across the base of the bill.  Sometimes called the "butcher bird", this predatory songbird has the unique habit of impaling its prey, mostly insects, but occasionally small vertebrates such as mice or snakes on twigs or thorns.
          </p>
          <p>
            Research and management needs for the Loggerhead Shrike depends upon the spatial scale of study.  Across the species’ range, research is still needed to understand the causes of the population declines, but, these may vary.  For example, the impact of pesticides and other contaminants is likely a greater concern in the areas in which such agricultural practices are common.
          </p>
