    <h2>Habitat</h2>
    <p>
      The Loggerhead Shrike utilizes grassland habitats that vary from shrub-steppe in the western United States to pastureland in the eastern Canadian provinces of Ontario and Quebec (Pruitt 2000).  Shrikes hunt by scanning for prey from perches in open short-grass areas, and they prefer a combination of pasture or short grassland with scattered low trees and shrubs.  But, suitable ‘habitat’ also includes rural residential development, light industrial and business parks, cemeteries and suburban parks.
    </p>

    <p>
      The Carden Plain is regarded as one of the strongholds of the Loggerhead Shrike in Ontario. In the mid-1970's, an estimated 30 pairs were present in the Carden area (Pittaway 1991).  During the first Ontario Breeding Bird Atlas (OBBA, 1981 – 1985), one 10 x 10 km square was estimated to have more than 10 breeding pairs.  Shrike numbers fell to a low of 4 known breeding pairs in the mid-1990s in the area.  Its presence was again confirmed during the second OBBA survey (2000 – 2005).  Ten to fourteen breeding pairs have been located annually in recent years.  The Carden Plain is well known as an Important Bird Area (IBA) for many grassland bird species.
    </p>
