  <div class="col-md-6">
    <h2>Conservation</h2>
    <p>
      My research is undertaken in collaboration with the Canadian Wildlife Service and other partners across North America.  The goal of our research is to compare Loggerhead Shrike populations from across Canada and the United States to examine migratory behaviour, identify key wintering areas and to understand the species’ population structure, including assessing age and sex biased dispersal and migration.
    </p>
    <p>
      We also assist the Eastern Loggerhead Shrike Recovery Team to answer conservation related questions that help guide recovery and management activities.  Work to date includes assessing and comparing historic and current genetic diversity of the captive population versus the wild population in Ontario; comparing genetic diversity estimates for the captive colony based on the ‘pedigree’ approach versus actual estimates of diversity using nuclear genetic markers; determining the need for augmentation of the captive population assure genetic viability; assessing if inbreeding depression is reducing viability of captive bred birds; and quantifying the genetically effective versus census population size of the wild isolated Ontario population with that of the relatively stable Colorado population.
    </p>
  </div>

